04459nam a22005775i 9780822395874DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223958747 a10.1515/97808223958742doi  a(DE-B1597)554489  a(OCoLC)840897778  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHV5809b.A335 2013 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a616.8622300aAddiction Trajectories /cWilliam Garriott, Eugene Raikhel. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b7 illustrations, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExperimental futures : technological lives, scientific arts, anthropological voices00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: TRACING NEW PATHS IN THE ANTHROPOLOGY OF ADDICTION -- tONE. THE ELEGIAC ADDICT -- tTWO. BALANCING ACTS -- tTHREE. A FEW WAYS TO BECOME UNREASONABLE -- tFOUR. PHARMACEUTICAL EVANGELISM AND SPIRITUAL CAPITAL -- tFIVE. ELUSIVE TRAVELERS -- tSIX. SIGNS OF SOBRIETY -- tSEVEN. PLACEBOS OR PROSTHESES FOR THE WILL? -- tEIGHT. ''YOU CAN ALWAYS TELL WHO'S USING METH'' -- tNINE. ''WHY CAN'T THEY STOP?'' -- tTEN. COMMITTED TO WILL -- tAFTERWORD. FOLLOWING ADDICTION TRAJECTORIES -- tREFERENCES -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing anthropological perspectives to bear on addiction, the contributors to this important collection highlight the contingency of addiction as a category of human knowledge and experience. Based on ethnographic research conducted in sites from alcohol treatment clinics in Russia to Pentecostal addiction ministries in Puerto Rico, the essays are linked by the contributors' attention to the dynamics-including the cultural, scientific, legal, religious, personal, and social-that shape the meaning of "addiction" in particular settings. They examine how it is understood and experienced among professionals working in the criminal justice system of a rural West Virginia community; Hispano residents of New Mexico's Espanola Valley, where the rate of heroin overdose is among the highest in the United States; homeless women participating in an outpatient addiction therapy program in the Midwest; machine-gaming addicts in Las Vegas, and many others. The collection's editors suggest "addiction trajectories" as a useful rubric for analyzing the changing meanings of addiction across time, place, institutions, and individual lives. Pursuing three primary trajectories, the contributors show how addiction comes into being as an object of knowledge, a site of therapeutic intervention, and a source of subjective experience.Contributors. Nancy D. Campbell, E. Summerson Carr, Angela Garcia, William Garriott, Helena Hansen, Anne M. Lovell, Emily Martin, Todd Meyers, Eugene Raikhel, A. Jamie Saris, Natasha Dow Schüll  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAddictsxRehabilitation. 0aSubstance abusexResearch. 0aSubstance abusexTreatment. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aGarriott, William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRaikhel, Eugene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395874zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395874.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles